My BFF and I took my cousin to the World of Coke on yesterday to celebrate her birthday.  We had a great time. But our favorite Coke Ambassador was CHARLY in the Milestone room. She was so full of energy and knowledge.  We were fascinated with this young lady. We couldn't believe she had memorized all this Coke history.  She made it fun to listen to.  She needs to train the other Ambassadors. Thank you CHARLY for an awesome experience.  We learned so much about Coke yesterday.

(Translated by Google) The museum is an impressive merchandising warehouse, which tells you from the beginning what is going to happen: they take a photograph of you that you know they will sell you at the end for a crazy price. After a couple of waiting rooms and a 15-minute commercial, they leave you free to visit and revisit different rooms, among which are: 1) A vault that supposedly contains the secret formula, but which leads to taking a photo with a locked vault. 2) A fictitious bottling plant that leads to nothing. 3) A room that misses the influence of Coca-Cola in pop culture. 4) A screening room for a 3D movie that is only in 2D and is actually an extended commercial. 5) The finishing touch is a store where, not happy with the high price of admission, they fill you with advertising at a high price. If you want Coca-Cola merch or a souvenir, it's better to go straight to the store.  The two high points are the testing room, where you can try different flavors of drinks produced in different parts of the world, and the attention of a large part of the staff who, in general, are friendly and attentive.  If you are an unconditional lover of Coca-Cola, you will not suffer, but you will not be entertained either. If you want an entertaining museum with interesting content, it is not recommended. It was nice to visit this spot of Atlanta. However, I expected more from this place and felt a bit disappointed. I think the historic part, the taste room, and the gift shop are good, but some processes make the visit a little awkward. When I passed the entrance, there was a lounge room with a clock showing the wait time for the next group to enter the museum. Waited about 15 minutes. During the wait time, an employee makes quizzes to try entertaining the visitors. Once we enter the museum, there is another wait room where another employee also tries entertaining people during 15 minutes by talking and showing some historic objects. Next, a movie theater room is open and exhibits a 15-minute ad movie. Only after these you are free to visit the museum. The 3-D movie room was actually in 2-D, and it was another boring ad movie. In summary, It was nice to be there, since I am from another State and country, but the experience could be more pleasant by providing more freedom and fun activities to the visitors. I have been to the humble town of Waco-TX at a competitor brand's museum and my experience was memorable. I am sure Coca-Cola can improve and make this "World of Coca-Cola" better.
Very Nice and interesting place to visit!!

This is one of Atlanta's main attractions and it's worth the hype. It can be pretty crowded though, so try to hit it at opening time, or later in the afternoon if you want fewer people there. Among the attractions are timelines of the Coca Cola company's history, demonstrations of how the drink is bottled, and a chance to have your picture taken with the Coca Cola Bear (although this is pretty pricey). And of course, the famous Coke tasting room, where you can try different drinks from around the world! It's finally back after being shut down or limited due to the pandemic.

This is my second time visiting. My first time was when I was in middle school. I took my little sister and cousin and enjoyed it just the same as an adult.  The scent room wasn‚Äôt open but will open back up in March. The staff are very friendly and express the spirit of coca-cola. The door ambassador that started the journey kept us engaged and excited about our experience.  There was a lot of people there as it was MLK weekend when we took our visit. The taste it room is fun. The videos are full of adventure and does a good job at drawing you in to the experience. It was nice to get refreshed on the experience of coca-cola. I highly recommend experiencing this place and the Georgia Aquarium on the same day. They are located right beside each other.  Make sure you are thirty when you go so that you can taste as many flavors as possible of coca-cola products. There is a lot of history to learn during this tour and experience. You can buy your tickets there. We didn‚Äôt wait it line long to purchase tickets.
